ion in 1980, which introduced the multi-axial diagnostic system>", "DSM-III-R:", "DSM-IV:The DSM-IV, or the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fourth Edition, is a widely recognized diagnostic manual used primarily in the United States for the classification, diagnosis, and treatment of mental health and psychiatric disorders. It provides standardized criteria for a range of conditions, including hysteria, obsessive-compulsive disorder, somatoform disorders, specific phobias, and other fear-related conditions. Clinicians and psychiatrists rely on the DSM-IV to diagnose psychiatric illnesses based on clinical symptoms and diagnostic criteria, making it a critical tool in mental health practice. The manual has been utilized in various studies, such as the survey conducted by Gabe et al. and Fink, to determine the prevalence of specific disorders like somatoform disorders. While the DSM-IV shares similarities with the ICD-10 in its classification system, it remains a distinct and authoritative resource in the field of mental health diagnostics."], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-v3"}}}